---
import GuideLayout from '../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro';
import { simulate } from '../../lib/snowball.js';

const fmt = (n: number) => '$' + Math.round(n).toLocaleString('en-US');
const fmt2 = (n: number) => '$' + n.toLocaleString('en-US', { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
// $5,000 at 24% APR
const BAL = 5000, APR = 24;
const daily = APR / 100 / 365;
const monthlyInterest = (BAL * APR) / 100 / 12;
// min payment ~ interest + 1% of balance ≈ $150 typical
const minOnly = simulate([{ name: 'card', balance: BAL, rate: APR, minPayment: 150 }], 0, 'snowball');
const with250 = simulate([{ name: 'card', balance: BAL, rate: APR, minPayment: 150 }], 100, 'snowball');
const yrMo = (m: number) => `${Math.floor(m / 12)} yr ${m % 12} mo`;
---

<GuideLayout
  title="How Credit Card Interest Is Calculated (and Why Minimums Barely Move It)"
  metaTitle="How Credit Card Interest Works — Daily Compounding Explained | Payoff Logic"
  description="Credit card interest explained with real numbers: daily periodic rates, average daily balance, the grace-period rule, and how long $5,000 at 24% takes on minimum payments."
  slug="how-credit-card-interest-works"
  updated="July 11, 2026"
  updatedISO="2026-07-11"
  kind="payoff"
  tool={{ href: '/debt-snowball-calculator/', label: 'debt snowball calculator' }}
>
  <div class="answer">
    <strong>Direct answer:</strong> Cards charge interest daily: your APR ÷ 365 (the
    daily periodic rate) is applied to each day's balance, then summed for the cycle. A
    {fmt(BAL)} balance at {APR}% APR accrues roughly {fmt2(monthlyInterest)} a month —
    so a $150 payment retires only ~{fmt2(150 - monthlyInterest)} of debt. Hold a fixed $150 payment and this card takes {yrMo(minOnly.months)} to kill; add $100/month and
    it's {yrMo(with250.months)}.
  </div>

  <h2>The daily mechanics</h2>
  <p>
    A {APR}% APR is really a {(daily * 100).toFixed(4)}% <em>daily</em> rate. Each day,
    the card multiplies that rate by your balance and adds it to an interest bucket;
    most issuers use the "average daily balance" method, so a mid-cycle purchase
    accrues interest for exactly the days it's on the books. Because yesterday's
    interest joins today's balance at cycle end, card interest compounds — effectively
    turning a {APR}% APR into roughly {((Math.pow(1 + daily, 365) - 1) * 100).toFixed(1)}%
    per year if you never pay it down.
  </p>

  <h2>The grace period — the only free lunch in consumer credit</h2>
  <p>
    If you pay the <em>statement balance in full</em> by the due date, purchases accrue
    no interest at all: that's the grace period. Carry even $1 forward, and most cards
    revoke it — new purchases start accruing from day one until you've paid in full
    for a cycle or two. This cliff is why "I'll just carry a small balance this month"
    costs more than the small balance suggests. (Carrying a balance also does nothing
    for your credit score — utilization is reported either way.)
  </p>

  <h2>Why minimum payments are designed to be slow</h2>
  <p>
    Typical minimums are interest + 1% of the balance (or a $25–$40 floor). On our
    {fmt(BAL)} example that starts around $150 — of which {fmt2(monthlyInterest)} is
    interest. The principal dent is tiny, and as the balance falls the minimum falls
    too, stretching the timeline. Even holding the payment FIXED at $150 (already better than a declining minimum), it takes <strong>{yrMo(minOnly.months)}</strong> and <strong>{fmt(minOnly.totalInterest)}</strong> of interest to clear {fmt(BAL)}; a true declining-minimum track runs years longer — every statement's "minimum payment warning" box exists because Congress made
    issuers print this math.
  </p>
  <div class="tablewrap"><table>
    <thead><tr><th>Strategy on {fmt(BAL)} @ {APR}%</th><th class="num">Time to zero</th><th class="num">Total interest</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Fixed $150/month</td><td class="num">{yrMo(minOnly.months)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(minOnly.totalInterest)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Fixed $250/month</td><td class="num">{yrMo(with250.months)}</td><td class="num">{fmt(with250.totalInterest)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></div>

  <h2>Cutting the cost, in order of impact</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Stop the meter:</strong> a 0% balance-transfer card (12–21 months, 3–5% fee) or a fixed-rate consolidation loan converts daily compounding into a plain amortizing loan.</li>
    <li><strong>Fix your payment:</strong> paying a constant amount (not the declining minimum) is what collapses the timeline — the table above is the proof.</li>
    <li><strong>Sequence multiple cards:</strong> highest APR first saves the most; smallest first builds momentum. The <a href="/debt-snowball-calculator/">snowball calculator</a> shows both on your actual cards, and the <a href="/guides/snowball-vs-avalanche/">snowball-vs-avalanche guide</a> explains when each wins.</li>
    <li><strong>Ask for a rate cut:</strong> issuers grant APR reductions more often than people expect, especially with on-time history.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Card debt vs. every other debt</h2>
  <p>
    At {APR}%, no mortgage prepayment, car-loan extra, or index-fund expectation
    competes — retiring card debt is the highest guaranteed return most households
    will ever see. Put the card first, then point the freed-up payment at the next
    goal with the <a href="/loan-payoff-calculator/">loan payoff calculator</a>.
  </p>
</GuideLayout>
